1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian Smithsonian NMAAHC.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:16,000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:26,000
I'm in North Charleston, South Carolina with John Bishop, our videographer on Thursday, June the 9th, 2011.

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:39,000
We are here to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian's Smithsonian NMAAHC and the Library of Congress.

5
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:51,000
Our interview today will be conducted by Prof. Kerry Taylor, Dept. of History, The Citadel here in Charleston, and we're delighted to have Kerry with us to contribute.

6
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:58,000
We are here today to interview William Saunders, and with that I think, Kerry, I will turn it over to you. Thank you.

7
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Mr. Saunders, to start us out, could you tell us where and when you were born?

8
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:19,000
I was born in New York City in 1935. I was sent to Johns Island, South Carolina when I was 18 months old on a train with a tag to be picked up on Johns Island where my grandfather picked me up.

9
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:26,000
You sent from New York City to Charleston to be with your grandparent?

10
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:36,000
My grandparent's on Johns Island, South Carolina. Charleston, this is where the train went. My mother was from Johns Island, South Carolina, she moved to New York, and that's where I was born.

11
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Now did you have brothers and sisters? Come a little bit more about that.

12
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:49,000
At that point, I guess I had three brothers and sisters. Later on I had another brother that was born.

13
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:56,000
My brothers and sisters was on Johns Island, South Carolina when I came. They were living with their father and grandfather. The other side of the family.

14
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
But you were raised by your grandparent?

15
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:04,000
My mother's father and mother.

16
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Tell me a little bit about Johns Island, South Carolina in the 1930s and the 1940s. What kind of a place was it like to grow up?

17
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:23,000
I think Dr. Kerry [Taylor] looking at it now from looking at it then because at that time it was not all that nice of place now.

18
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:28,000
It seems to be a paradise compared to a long time ago.

19
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:37,000
But we ate everything from the river, from the world to grow everything. And everybody had access to the land.

20
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:45,000
You go to the river, you go to the woods, hunt, there were barriers and so many things grew wild nuts.

21
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:52,000
And everything was just so good as I looked back over. It was a good place to grow up.

22
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Now tell me your grandparents, your grandfather was a farmer?

23
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:03,000
Yeah, he was a farmer. But he died when I was seven. He died in 1943.

24
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:11,000
So I was just eight years old when he died. But he was a farmer. He was really an unusual fellow.

25
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:19,000
He used to survey land, had no formal education. But he used to survey land for other people.

26
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:27,000
And he had something made like an A. And he could wind that around every time he'd do it five or six times. That's an acre.

27
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:35,000
And we got trees, he was playing trees at those places. And those things are still there today. He was really good.

28
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:44,000
We just beginning to get black civil in the years now. For a long time we had none. But coming from Africa, they had their own things.

29
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:49,000
And John Psyll, this was predominantly an African-American community that you grew up in?

30
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Yes, you know, on Johns Island, South Carolina, it's probably been at that point about 75-80% African-American.

31
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And one of the things that my grandparents and all the elders would tell young blacks is that you can do anything that you want to.

32
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,000
But you've got to stay away from white men because you can't get in trouble. You can't win no matter what you do.

33
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:19,000
You can't win and be understood that. So there were very little conflict within those times.

34
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:31,000
You know, I talked a little bit earlier. It was so much fun. You made your own toys. You used to have cans that you could hold in and roll and make noise like motors and all that stuff.

35
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:37,000
And we used to work from what they call 'can to can't, from the time you're can seen them until you can't see at night.

36
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:44,000
We had no fat people because everybody worked. Ain't a whole lot of food, but everybody worked very physically.

37
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:50,000
You know, focused to work and tell somebody to pass out.

38
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:58,000
From what age would you begin to come to Charleston or what would bring you to Charleston as a young person?

39
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:08,000
God, when I first got, yes, I really came to Charleston. It's that I got burned. I was supposed to come to Charleston to buy some shoes.

40
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:15,000
My brother was older than me. So I never got any new clothes. Everything I got was what he had.

41
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:25,000
And then God made it that my feet grew bigger than his. They had to send me the charts and the bison. Use shoes. You know, nobody got new shoes.

42
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:33,000
There was a place that used to get old shoes and they would redo it. And I stood before a fire and got my leg on fire burned myself up.

43
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:40,000
I was pretty bad and they had to take me to the doctor. That's how it came to Charleston. I had that first time.

44
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:48,000
How did you relate? I was in the winter time and everybody used to have fire by the road waiting to get a ride on a truck of bus that was coming by.

45
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:58,000
And I stood too close to the fire and it caught my plans on fire and it burned me pretty bad. Got some bad scars from that.

46
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:10,000
You eventually came to Charleston for high school? Well, that was a long time. I came to Charleston many times before that because we had a farm.

47
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:17,000
And then we started bringing stuff to the market itself. I used to even sell something called Lightwood and you know what Lightwood was.

48
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:24,000
But it's the inner side of a pine tree that died and you cut it up and you use it to start fire.

49
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:32,000
It was like what they call spinoffs now but you can light it and it has like oil in it. And I used to cut that and use the sandals for 10 cents a bunch.

50
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,000
And I used to bring it to Charleston 10-15 bunch of it. I had a dollar and 20 cents.

51
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:46,000
I used to also been chicken and we were talking early. Things has changed so much. My grandmother will give me two chickens to bring to the market.

52
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:54,000
And I would get five dollars for those two chickens. You can imagine that was very, very expensive. Eggs was dollar and something at that.

53
00:06:54,000 --> 00:07:06,000
Nobody that grew chicken ate chicken. You know, we brought the chicken to the market. You sold it and then the people that bought it would give you back the heart, deliver and all of those stuff.

54
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:14,000
And then that goes back and my grandparents and would make a real stew out of that with black pepper and onion and garlic.

55
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:21,000
And they made it so good that we could make each seven to bad health. I mean, it was really, really good stuff.

56
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:31,000
Now I know that Esau Jenkins was someone who you know, who you have a long history with and has had a big impact on your life.

57
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:37,000
Do you remember how old you were when you met Esau Jenkins under what circumstance?

58
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:48,000
Well, he was the son of school superintendent and the teacher and when the class is. So I knew him from the time I started going to church five, six years old.

59
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:58,000
And he was also always involved in the politics of things. Our school didn't have any, you know, no lights or anything.

60
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:05,000
And he had to contract to bring wood to the school where we used to catch fire and weapons and stuff like that.

61
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:18,000
And also, and with the, excuse me, the bus that when kids got a chance to go to Burke High School Charleston School Charleston, because we couldn't go to the White High School on Johns Island, South Carolina, he ended with a contract to bring down kids over to this school.

62
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:29,000
But Esau did so many amazing things because he was a businessman. He ran for the Constituent District 9 School Board.

63
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:40,000
They've never been another election hell from 56 to 70. They just stopped having election. That was one of the most, I'm still trying to find today how you stop having election in America.

64
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:49,000
But they did. And all they did is anytime somebody wanted off, they had disappointed a new person, a new white male, but it just went on.

65
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:51,000
To keep these off the family.

66
00:08:51,000 --> 00:09:04,000
Well, no, but to keep blacks and off the board after I did some studies in this, been in the last few years, they stopped having election all over Charleston County, because they were afraid at that point that blacks were going to get elected to school board.

67
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:19,000
And when Stokely Carmichael and some of them, and we skipping some stuff, or when Stokely Carmichael came to Johns Island, South Carolina in 1967, we had to start making decisions that we wanted some blacks on the school board in District 9.

68
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:30,000
And so what we did, we told them we wanted three people on the board. We gave them the names of those three people. And we said, you don't have to do it, then we're going to hold on the election.

69
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:36,000
And we set it up, we're going to hold on the black election, we have a black school board, and we have a white school board.

70
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:46,000
So what they did to avoid that, they appointed one person that we wanted, and they appointed Esau Jenkins to that board. From 56, this was 68. So they appointed him.

71
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:59,000
And they appointed him for one reason that Esau Jenkins and I was getting along pretty bad at that point. And that's what the reason they appointed Esau was one of the founders of SCLC with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr stayed on Johns Island, South Carolina with us.

72
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:12,000
My wife did the cooking, all that stuff. But I was a part of Stokely Carmichael and the student on Valorant, like Malcolm X. So those two group was not mixing. And they appointed Esau, so Esau and I can have a fight.

73
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:22,000
Yeah. What were the kinds of things that began to contribute to your political sensibilities as a young person?

74
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:36,000
Well, I caught so much hill as a young person and having some ambition. My grandmother gave me, I think, back in probably 49, a couple of acres of land that I could plant for myself.

75
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:45,000
And I was catching the bus trying to get them after graduating from elementary school and then went to the ninth grade and trying to do farm.

76
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:55,000
And I couldn't even come up with the money to buy lunch and stuff like that. And the kids in Charleston teased us so much the way that we dressed, the way that we talked.

77
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:05,000
I mean, we were just really outcasts at this high school. And the second year, they had a sophomore, a group of us got together and decided to volunteer for the Army.

78
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:15,000
And I was 16 at that time, but they really didn't care like they don't today. They let my age be 18 and I was able to go into the military.

79
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:24,000
I went to Fort Jackson, South Carolina SC + Fort Jackson, South Carolina SC + Fort Lewis Tacoma WA Tacoma WA and then it was one of the most amazing things to California, [got] down the plane. And went to Hawaii, took my basic training in Hawaii.

80
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:34,000
And only volunteers could go there. And my suffering, after I looked back at it, I suffered more racism in the United States Army than I've suffered any place.

81
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:44,000
In my life before or after in a distance. Well, let's go for your barracks in Hawaii. And we left right from there, went straight to Korean War, no vacation, no nothing.

82
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:55,000
Went straight to war. And they took us in on LST where they dropped the front of it in the water where you run up on the beach with guns and bare nets and stuff like that.

83
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:06,000
And that's one of the scariest things. And you and I were talking earlier, that's still having flashback with some of that stuff. But were you about three miles away from fighting anybody? Go ahead.

84
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:13,000
You confronted more racism in Hawaii than you had encountered in Johns Island, South Carolina or in Charleston.

85
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:27,000
How why and the military and even in Korean War, racism was real, real bad in Korean War. And Hawaii and I just realized later on, it was right after 1951, they had just really integrated the Army.

86
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:40,000
There were four blacks in our company, one Hispanic, one Indian. And we were the really, and I didn't realize until many years later that all of these people, poor white men, who also had a lot of problems.

87
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:50,000
And the only place that they could invent any of those problems was on people like me. So they had their own problem reason. And we had a lot of fights with that.

88
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:55,000
What kinds of people do you remember particular instances?

89
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:11,000
I had physical fights and a guy would beat me. But my grandmother, a bad temper. I get real mad. I don't give up. So I don't stop when people say to stop. So I ain't a being the one getting in trouble.

90
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:21,000
But they did so many things to the blacks. I had one guy, one of my best friends who died recently. They made him dig a six by six by six hole.

91
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:28,000
And then they saw him drop a dime and then they can close it up. You know, those things, they're trying to stop.

92
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:43,000
And it's a lot of it coming back to me more and more knowledge is having a lot of flags back with that. Even in Korean War and the war, I mean, this guy might first sergeant who I didn't know on the front line.

93
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:53,000
We just fought for two days. And I was going up the hill on top. And he said to your black center, if you come up here, I blew your brains out. And he had a 45 on me.

94
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:05,000
And I decided at the point I was carrying my rifle was in the hole. I was going to roll and get my gun. You know, like you saw some of the movies. And I said, that hole, that 45 blow, whole straight through you.

95
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:20,000
Because I seen 45 sharp people going to throw a hole back out. I went back to my hole and stayed there. When it was time for us to leave, he sent for me and said that I had made me leave the whole company out.

96
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:32,000
And of course, being in front, you get killed first. So he makes sure that that was in front going out. Those kinds of stuff. So there's a lot of stuff that we can lie about because if you don't, you cry about it.

97
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:43,000
So, but the racism is just really heavy. Coming back, even in the California, when we got back as heroes, because I got wounded and believe it, they're in California.

98
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:55,000
They start calling out to white soldiers name. And then they call the black soldiers. I never understood that until we got on. But black and white soldiers couldn't ride in the same train coach across America.

99
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:09,000
So you had to ride in separate coaches. And I got into Fort Jackson, South Carolina SC + Fort Jackson, South Carolina SC + Fort Lewis Tacoma WA Tacoma WA. I was in the hospital for four months, but for my wound. So I got paid, got about $500, which was a monumental amount of money back in those days.

100
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:20,000
And we went into Columbia, South Carolina. And I ran it to the Greyhound bus station. My buddy kept it back. And I ran it to the Greyhound bus station. And the cop came to me with his gun, pushed down.

101
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:27,000
He said, boy, what's wrong with you? You know you don't belong in here. And I never knew that I didn't belong in the Greyhound bus station.

102
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:37,000
I never left Benoffa, Johns Island, South Carolina to go through that kind of segregation. And I said, no, I didn't know I didn't belong here. We do I belong.

103
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:47,000
And he showed me the back of the bus station where black sport tickets outside. And when the bus comes, white loaded in the bus. And he see the left in the back.

104
00:15:47,000 --> 00:16:00,000
And we had access to those things. And my bitterness really began that time really hard. I just didn't understand it. And I used to call all whites racist at that point.

105
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:14,000
Because he's some guy that I was with for a year. And yet no, no, when I'm saying, we're building, let me get the ticket for you. Or let him get this ticket. Nobody's ever won. I know all of my white friends just dropped it here. And nobody said anything.

106
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:31,000
So it became self-curilinians upon returning. Yeah. I got everything with it. You know, only place that I've ever really been an American was basically in Hawaii, a little bit there and Korean War and in Japan. I've never been an American in America.

107
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:35,000
I've always been a second class citizen in America.

108
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:53,000
Tell me about your, your, your four one of your, your injury. Well, I stepped on a, a, a booby trap on the God December 26, 1951. It'll never go away. And I wasn't really all thing because I was assistant squad leader. And the snow was almost too fee deep.

109
00:16:53,000 --> 00:17:05,000
And the rule was everybody walking the same, the squad leader walks there and everybody 14 men walk right in that same track. And I was the last man in the thing and it went off on me.

110
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:20,000
It's really a good, that's the kind of luck I practice most of my life. And you know, it hit me and I went up, it hit my M-1 rifle and busted and high off. And then it was what, it's what you call a booby trap trip flare.

111
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:31,000
And then it went way up about 50 feet up in the air and lit up. And that's how they used to shoot people because they would show you where you are. And I laid, I knew I lost my leg and I felt it was there.

112
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:45,000
And some of the soldiers said, well, we want to go get a stretcher for you and take you back, send no out walk. So the medic said, well, nothing wrong with me because I couldn't walk or something was wrong. And by four o'clock at that money, we were attacked by the Korean.

113
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:58,000
We fought in Tampa 5, 6, 30 that morning. And my foot is swollen up so big as a person. And the medic said, well, we've sent you down to the ladder, check it. By the time I got to the age, the doctor said it's broken.

114
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:06,000
And they put me in a hospital airplane and a cheap then on the hospital airplane went to Japan spent four months in hospital.

115
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:22,000
I never returned to Korean War. Yeah, after my four months went back to Korean War on the front line. They changed the law. And all laws have always changed with me. Any time you got a broken bone, you went home except they changed the law right at that time.

116
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:30,000
Had nothing to do with me. He's just my luck with like that. I went back to Korean War for another two months.

117
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:38,000
So what were your intentions upon returning to South Carolina? What hopes or plans did you have?

118
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:52,000
Well, again, when I decided to still fighting like I'm doing today, I was about 19, then 18, 19. But I was still trying to be a man. And I wanted to do some stuff to prove that I was.

119
00:18:52,000 --> 00:19:03,000
So when I got the send me back to Fort Jackson, South Carolina SC + Fort Lewis Tacoma WA, Washington, the Tacoma, and I went to administrative school. I took typing and all kinds of administrative stuff.

120
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:16,000
And I'd been company clerk and I was able to make sergeant before I got this job. I was in charge sending up people to get promoted. So I was in charge of who got the eligible put in.

121
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:26,000
I made a lot of friends came back as sergeant. I ended up making sergeant in Fort Jackson, South Carolina SC + Fort Lewis Tacoma WA. And what I wanted to do, I felt like I could make a difference.

122
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:37,000
I wanted to be a man, not a black man. It's been years before I got the whole black thing. But I wanted to be a man. I want to prove that I was good enough. And that I could compete.

123
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:57,000
So when I came back up there on my joint with Esau Jenkins, we talked about some of that. But some of the laws that they're trying to make today with this vote ID, it goes back to that period of time when blacks had to read a part of the Constitution to get registered to vote.

124
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:16,000
I used to teach people how to read and write those things. But a lot of the folks that we had from Johns Island, South Carolina, you couldn't teach them to read. But they memorized the Constitution. And they were going to take the test and pass it. And then they were conscious when they did read so well. But she memorized the whole time.

125
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:36,000
A lot of things at that point just to prove we had the Progressive Club. And where people used to Esau Jenkins had an adult education school there. So I got to be business manager of the Progressive Club. And again, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr came over and stayed with us within the 50s.

126
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:57,000
In 1959, I went to Highlander Research Center, the Highlander Research Center in Monteagle, Tennessee. And they raided the place while I was there. And they arrested Septima Clark. I mean, they really physically abused the arrested to see a guy, Kaewon was taking off the jail.

127
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:18,000
And they took that all of that property that they had there. They had said Septima Clark. They were selling beer. Others and the charge of selling beer, the breaking the law. They had beer and sodas and crackers and stuff. And they had it out on the table. And you can get anything you want. Have you want to leave a donation you could about that. They lost all that property for that.

128
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:35,000
My bitterness continued right from the military continued to do so. And I wanted to they wanted to search all of the cars. And I refused to give them the keys and Esau Jenkins and I. DeQuincey Newman and they were there. They came and made me give them the guys the keys.

129
00:21:35,000 --> 00:22:04,000
Because I was making break open again. I get said that this nonviolent thing is not for me. I got to get out of this. And I left that 59. Back to Harlem again. But I really decided at that point, the nonviolent thing getting beat up for no reason is all not going to work for me. And I start searching there and I heard about my eyes. And then Stokely Carmichael. Some of these folks and I'm coming to Johns Island, South Carolina to see me.

130
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:20,000
Got a small enough to do it. It's not really doing it. So that's all it's back on. We're okay. Okay. Have that been your first visit to Harlem? Yeah, 1959. And what what what were the certain was it?

131
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:40,000
Esau Jenkins who facilitated that or how did you get it? Yeah, he's the purpose of the visit. Esau Jenkins. Those are running charge. But what they're doing or to go to Highland that they had brought people from all over the South. Just to sit and talk to each other. And because so many of the time we thought we had the worst problem and other people had different problems.

132
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:54,000
So I'm meeting with people from Appalachia, white, poor whites and really the just strip mining and all of that stuff. You know, we got a chance to see how poor people were being treated. Not black people or Indian, but it was about poor people.

133
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:05,000
It's still like it took a while before I got all the way where I needed to go with that. But I started looking at people and started looking at our country as a class system and not a race system.

134
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:34,000
It get to be race at the bottom, but most of the time it's not racial. It's crimes. But that was your first exposure to a larger movement. Right. White and black and everybody from all over the place that was really in the miles heart and who was the director of the house. Just a brilliant guy. He was able to work through the union and everything that was changing. He was a part of change. And he used to say to us, I got a little problem on my own now what he had then.

135
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:49,000
But he said, you can't help people to do things. Then you want to tell them what to do. You got to let them do what they think is best after you have helped them to get the way they need to start from. And he did a good job on that.

136
00:23:49,000 --> 00:24:04,000
So you, but already in 1959, you're beginning to question the, at least the nonviolent aspect of the mainstream civil rights movement.

137
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:17,000
Yeah, and I don't like the term nonviolent in that sense because most of us that was in that recall, you had to be violent or nonviolent. When we believed in nonviolent, we just didn't believe in people beating you up for nothing.

138
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:30,000
And that's a different, but it's never been clear for that. And I couldn't take, they came to me and you know, even doing some of this stuff and I spoke to all about turning you cheek. I only had one cheek. So I couldn't turn it.

139
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:38,000
Do you remember discussions with Esau Jenkins about this, you know, this difference in strategies?

140
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:50,000
Some, but he was really, really strong in that area. He and Dr. Martin Luther King Jr all of it, they really believed it was not a fad or anything, they really believed in that.

141
00:24:50,000 --> 00:25:04,000
And so I support, I did all of the work that they needed done for the nonviolent movement. I just didn't march. I just didn't do the other stuff, but the paperwork, the food, where we had it on Johns Island, South Carolina, where I did the supportive background stuff for that.

142
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:19,000
But I couldn't go out and get beat up. We had Fannie Lou Hamer. All of these people came and stayed on Johns Island, South Carolina. Fannie Lou, to the stories that I was just going through the other day that she was telling us a progressive club that she would be marching.

143
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:25,000
And that didn't get beat up very often because she was saying, hit my mother fuck out, kill you, hit my mother fuck out, kill you.

144
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:32,000
And so she was just walking around and doing that. And the cops would just look at it and say, that woman, they crazy, really messed up that woman.

145
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:38,000
But there was a lot of tactics that folk use not to get beat up.

146
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:41,000
What were you doing for work at the time?

147
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:53,000
I went back to high school and graduated from high school in 1956. I went to work in a mattress factory. And I made mattress for 20 years.

148
00:25:53,000 --> 00:26:03,000
And I wanted, at the school when I went back to school, I took Bricklaying, which I wanted as a background trade, which I could do.

149
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:12,000
But I wanted a job that folk couldn't come to just find me. If I was at post office in Navy Art, I could get fired anytime for just being involved in anything racial.

150
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:17,000
Making mattresses, there was no reason to get rid of me.

151
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:27,000
And my boss, Mr. Julius Walsh, I never, again, because I was working for him and he came to me one day and said, you lazy.

152
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:37,000
And I had the sort of small attitude. And he said, I like you. And he said, because lazy people come up with an easier way to do stuff.

153
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:48,000
He said, can I start in making things? Everybody takes two people to carry mattress back to the truck. I built a thing where we put 20 mattresses on and they take it.

154
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:57,000
All of the stuff that they used to do, I changed. The owner making me forment. And the wire stuff was going on. He even put a telephone by my sewing machine.

155
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:10,000
So I had my own private telephone while doing the movement. It was a very interesting thing. And I followed that right now that lazy people really get a whole lot more done than people just don't care.

156
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:15,000
They don't just like to work, you know. If there's another way to do it, I'll find it.

157
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:18,000
But your boss tolerated your activism?

158
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:31,000
Yeah, but not just tolerated. I kept educating them about what was going on. And I used to, I've been arrested so many times, five times. I actually been in jail.

159
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:40,000
I've been in jail because the officer that I didn't dim my lights went not only like the car had was dim lights. You know, I've been in jail for mufflers.

160
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:51,000
And a lot of time my boss used to let me take the truck home because cops would be waiting for me when I get off from work that they would arrest me for certain things.

161
00:27:51,000 --> 00:28:01,000
And I would go to jail. But that's the thing that start talking about writing, you know, when I did, I went into love religion and politics.

162
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:14,000
Because I knew at some point I was going to get killed by some of these people. And so I want people, my kids, exactly, to know who I was and what I'm still writing.

163
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:26,000
You began the low country news letter. And about when and why did you initiate that project?

164
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:40,000
There was a guy that's still and I think Miss Sonya and probably got some stuff on him. Dr. Howard Levy? Dr. Howard Levy was a captain in the army, dermatologist that refused to go to Vietnam.

165
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:52,000
And he was waiting to go to jail. He was working with some Campbell's food folks, Campbell food folk in Columbia. And he was putting out a small paper up there.

166
00:28:52,000 --> 00:29:08,000
And he came, we met and got him to come to Johns Island, South Carolina. We ran into the White High School because the Black High School that they were building 1951 really had the books in the library that have anything that schools should have.

167
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:16,000
So we went into the White High School and took pictures and showed the difference between the Black High School and the White High School.

168
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:27,000
We were able to publish those things. And then when Howard was going to jail, he gave me all his stuff. And American Friends Service Committee Committee was working helping me at that point.

169
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:43,000
And they were the one who had a press in North Carolina. And they gave me the press, the press of Biggest is a room of the 1890 or something or 1918, about the old old press. But we were able to use that. And that's how we were putting it.

170
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:53,000
We felt that the only way that you can really inform people is to be able to give them information. We had some folk that was close to us, a concerned citizen.

171
00:29:53,000 --> 00:30:11,000
One of our members were working at the Navy Yard. And we would do the, when we first started before we had the press, we would do it just a mimeograph. And then he would take the memograph to the neighborhood base. And then he would run off 50, 60 copies and bring it back that we could distribute in the community.

172
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:15,000
So that's how we got before we got the press, we were putting out information.

173
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:20,000
And at this point, your target audience was mostly John S Island and Wadmalaw?

174
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:24,000
Yeah, District 9, Johns Island and Wadmalaw.

175
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:27,000
And that was the focus of your organizing?

176
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:37,000
Yeah, just those two artists. Those were the target for us, District and the White Hour School system, where we were the majority of those schools.

177
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:44,000
But, you know, there was so many things going on politically that we needed to, that we wanted to be a part of.

178
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:51,000
And what we did, when we decided, when he saw Jenkins, and then got appointed to that school board, we backed to that.

179
00:30:51,000 --> 00:31:04,000
The leaders of Charleston came up with a scam. It is a scam that they still got in Rokin today. They decided that they were going to put together a consolidated school board.

180
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:12,000
We had eight school boards. They could get a consolidated school board and set it on top of those eight school boards.

181
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:19,000
They said they could leave those in place. But, their school board is going to be able to manage all of the money.

182
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:26,000
And they can do all of the teachers stuff. So it really took away all of the power. And then they made it at large voting.

183
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:34,000
And then a whole of Charleston County vote for those nine. And it hasn't changed. It's been 1960. It still hasn't changed.

184
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:48,000
Everybody got a vote on those members of that school board. And then in 1970, they started back having an election for these constituent boards, which began to be more and more powerless as days go.

185
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:54,000
And this had a election recently with some people that nobody ran for the board at all with vacancies.

186
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:01,000
But it's, and I still find that this is the only place in the country that you got a school system structured the way that it is.

187
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:09,000
And there's no way that anybody could ever do anything to make a difference with the Charleston County school system.

188
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:31,000
So, you know, I know that, for instance, the Millison Brown and her father with the NAACP were very active in bringing some of the desegregation cases that eventually led to the desegregation of the Charleston school.

189
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:43,000
So, I know that the NAACP was very involved in that effort. What role did you play during that time here in this larger question of school desegregation?

190
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:51,000
Well, during that time with the Millison Brown, and then that was mostly before my time in being involved in that.

191
00:32:51,000 --> 00:33:06,000
But the NAACP and most of those black groups before Dr. Martin Luther King Jr had an interest in just certain kids, certain colored kids going to school with whites.

192
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:11,000
It had nothing to do with the broader scope of all kids going to school.

193
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:24,000
And again, that's why Dr. Martin Luther King Jr and I mean, NAACP had such a problem with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr because he was for everybody, he was talking about everybody having access to a good education.

194
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:37,000
But when the Brown v. Board of Education in Charleston, they had two schools, ICS and Avery Normal Institute, which were structured for the elite black kids.

195
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:46,000
And people like me had access to any of those kinds of schools. And when those schools were going out of business, that's when the integration stuff.

196
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:52,000
But it was not for me, it was for a certain group of folk in Charleston to go to those schools.

197
00:33:52,000 --> 00:34:02,000
And that's why I liked the first Supreme Court decision on desegregation where people could go if they wanted to or go to school nearest to them.

198
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:07,000
Then when they changed it to integration that you had to go, that I was against busing.

199
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:15,000
The same way like George Wallace, I have my same identity people being bus 40 miles because they're integrating something.

200
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:22,000
So I made a lot of enemies with the black leaders of Charleston, they really, really hated me.

201
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:29,000
I fought against integration in 1965. I said American-eated integration, not black people.

202
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:35,000
And Americans telling people all over the world that it's doing all these beautiful things for everybody.

203
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:43,000
So we don't need to fight for that. And he saw in all of those folk that a real serious problem with me.

204
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:50,000
And they actually believed that if black kids and white kids went to the same school, they was going to learn the same way.

205
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:53,000
They'd be taught the same way. They were so wrong with that.

206
00:34:53,000 --> 00:35:07,000
But again, they beat me up. I ran for the Office of Economic Opportunity Commission Board in 1967 and the black leadership of Charleston took a petition to the governor and said that not to certify me.

207
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:17,000
I won the election, but had to be certified by the governor, the black leaders with NAACP here in Charleston asked him not to certify me.

208
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:18,000
And he didn't.

209
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:24,000
This is for the Office of Economic Opportunity, the regional board.

210
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:34,000
Yeah, the local Charleston County board. And I won. And then after I refused to, they wouldn't certify me. I still went as a member.

211
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:45,000
And there was a black lady, Henrietta Canty from Georgia. She eventually ran for mayor then. But she came and I told her at this meeting that I was not certified.

212
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:52,000
And she closed up a book and Charleston kind of thing was getting a million dollars in for the Office of Economic Opportunity project.

213
00:35:52,000 --> 00:36:00,000
She said, when you certify him, call me. And she left. And then they came to me and said, well, you go through another election.

214
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:09,000
I said, no. When they tried some other tactics, didn't work. Then the governor said, well, I'm not going to certify anybody anymore.

215
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:18,000
So I was able to serve for that. They got even with Miss Canti too. I mean, these folks were really angry with her.

216
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:27,000
They did stuff that America does so well. They promoted her. So she would never be out in the field anymore to be in the VOLV.

217
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:36,000
She's got a good job. But that was one of those things that I really, they really saw me as a militant.

218
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:40,000
But Sylvia, I can't integrate. How could you be again integration?

219
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:53,000
So it's on the issue of non-violent self-defense, also school integration, you diverge from the mainstream civil rights leaders locally.

220
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:59,000
Yeah. See, my thing was really my own commands. And I meant to say that when we started, I think about human rights.

221
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:10,000
And I have never gotten past that. I let folks use me as civil rights. But you have to really have human rights before you can get any damn civil rights.

222
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:17,000
And most people have not gotten there yet. It was going well for a while, but it's not there anymore.

223
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:24,000
When did you first become aware of some issues taking place down at the medical college?

224
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:34,000
Again, one of those newsletters that you saw a lot ago, we've been meeting with some people down there. And we saw the condition of some of those women.

225
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:47,000
And some of the other people, some of the black men that was working there from the island. And we saw also the South Carolina in terms of the wouldn't pay minimum wage, those kinds of stuff.

226
00:37:47,000 --> 00:38:00,000
So we started to look for reason to help. And when they fired, I think it was five black nurses for not doing what they knew, they was not supposed to do what they wanted to do.

227
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:11,000
They fired them. They came to me and I was able to help them get reinstated. There was a guy named Reginald Barrett. He was on the civil rights commission.

228
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:22,000
He was able to get them reinstated. And then we felt at a point that we could really, these five nurses were so good that they stood up.

229
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:30,000
There were so many people that didn't have the guts to stand up. So that's when we decided that we wanted to see if we can organize them.

230
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:37,000
And we started organizing at Mr. Barrett's house. We told the five that was fired and that we were six of them all together.

231
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:46,000
Would they bring six people? And they brought six people. Next week we asked them what y'all did to 12, bring 12. They did until we couldn't meet at his house anymore.

232
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:57,000
We started meeting at the sector, the sick off factory, the DPO hall, and we got to the point that we organized, God we had about 300 people in that organization.

233
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:03,000
And they came together for what reason? What was the pretext of their...

234
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:04,000
These meetings.

235
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:18,000
Well money, but also respect. And they had in the hospital, they had places where, you know, blacks ate the lunch in the boiler room and all of those kinds of stuff.

236
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:31,000
So they really wanted to respect, but also there were no job craftifications. You would find some place where a nurse's aide was making more than a nurse of practical license, practical nurse.

237
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:39,000
It depends on whether the supervisor likes you or not. The con... I mean they had no job description and they did those things.

238
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:45,000
So we want to make sure that all of those things was changed and that people would treat it like people.

239
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:51,000
And that was a real, real hard thing for a lot of folks to understand.

240
00:39:51,000 --> 00:40:02,000
And I think that you would find that again, that group of blacks that I was talking about that had a problem with me, never got involved with this organizing.

241
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:10,000
And E. Sock Jenkins came in almost at the end of it. He did a lot of work in it coming down to the end of it and helping out.

242
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:16,000
But they didn't... they didn't see if we did not participate under those circumstances.

243
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:18,000
Because...

244
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:28,000
Most of the people called me. You know, most folks understand me. I got a lot of enemies and I keep telling people, I mean them all myself.

245
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:37,000
You know, I mean people didn't come at me. I almost all the time. When are people? When are they in a way that it caused them to be angry?

246
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:44,000
Not me. And that's... they used it as an excuse. They didn't like the tactics or any of those things.

247
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:52,000
That mostly was about me and the mill... And the other person was that we had some leaders that wanted to leave them with also Black Muslim, Otis Robinson.

248
00:40:52,000 --> 00:41:01,000
And he was the leader of the Muslim here. And he was really an elegant speaker and he could really do stuff with people.

249
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:09,000
The night that Dr. Martin Luther King Jr got killed, I mean he talked to us for real about... because we had about 200 people in the...

250
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:15,000
And he instructed them about going home. Then other trouble he could get killed tonight because there was going to be going on.

251
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:27,000
And they did all of the stuff that we needed he did. The president of the hospital sent out a notice that he would never do anything for these people.

252
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:37,000
Because they are not important to the hospital. You know, we don't even need them. And they came back. They were so hurt and down and older stole them.

253
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:44,000
That you are somebody. Jesse Jackson. But he's... you are somebody. Although you don't operate on people and all the stuff.

254
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:52,000
But you're with the patient 24 hours a day. You clean them, you feed them, you talk to them. You're with them. You are somebody. You are somebody.

255
00:41:52,000 --> 00:41:56,000
And that's how that whole thing that I am somebody came out and I noticed Robinson.

256
00:41:56,000 --> 00:41:57,000
That was what it's Robinson.

257
00:41:57,000 --> 00:41:58,000
That was what it's Robinson.

258
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:05,000
That was him. He did that. He really fired up folk in terms of being proud of themselves.

259
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:11,000
The kind of job that they didn't matter that they weren't operating. That he was telling the surgeon to be with the guy.

260
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:16,000
10 minutes. You with them 24 hours a day. Now who's the most important to this person?

261
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:19,000
So that's how we got to the point where that hospital worker.

262
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:26,000
And we finally, you know, they forced the issue that we had to call in the union and SCLC came in.

263
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:34,000
But when they came in, we were. The people were organized. All they did, they started working with the people in the community.

264
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:38,000
And the piles to be. But we had the people together.

265
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:53,000
But for several months, a group of mostly black women and other low wage hospital workers as well as their community supporters had been meeting at the DPO ball.

266
00:42:53,000 --> 00:43:00,000
Yeah. And you know, and people keep saying mostly women, but they were a lot of men.

267
00:43:00,000 --> 00:43:11,000
They are the lives and the cooks and all of these folk were men. This thing about women being just enjoyed and did all of this stuff then started in 1980 something.

268
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:19,000
But it was a complete community effort. I got arrested with them the first night at that hospital.

269
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:27,000
So I can they put us we all were talking earlier. They put us in a cell with no windows, no, you know, just this one door.

270
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:31,000
I was in there with some guys and I'm across the four big.

271
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:37,000
You know, and I'm looking at they looking at me as the leader and I was I was really out of it.

272
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:42,000
And I had guys that was with me for two years almost started singing.

273
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:47,000
And then someone started telling jokes. And then we're just finding people start laughing and stuff.

274
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:53,000
And they came and took us out of that cell and put us in a lit of cell.

275
00:43:53,000 --> 00:44:00,000
And it was one of those things that really impressed me in terms of there is something that all of us could do.

276
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:06,000
If you break your turn, there's something because I was a handicapped telling handicapped with that.

277
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:18,000
And I wanted to go back to the workers because when we had some white workers came to join the union and the black were afraid of them because they thought of them up being spies.

278
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:24,000
And we, you know, I be knew they were spies because we knew who the spies were. They were black.

279
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:28,000
And we had some covered. We were dealing with them.

280
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:32,000
But when these whites went back to work, they didn't have a job anymore.

281
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:37,000
And they never saw that anymore because the spies told who they were and what they were.

282
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:43,000
And I think when I looked at it again, it was so hard for me that I missed it.

283
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:50,000
Because those folks had special restroom. They had lunch and all of that stuff in the hospital. But they weren't making any money.

284
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:57,000
They couldn't do anything for their family that the other workers couldn't do. They were making the same money, except giving the special privilege.

285
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:00,000
And so these two groups would be dancing together.

286
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:07,000
And I started really taking a close look at the class system of our government.

287
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:13,000
At what point did SCLC enter into the picture?

288
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:22,000
Along with the union and SCLC came together. They came about in January 1969.

289
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:28,000
And this is local 1199 who came out of New York and based in New York.

290
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:37,000
They were working hand in hand in New York with SCLC, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr, was involved in some of those kinds of stuff.

291
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:43,000
And they had some very powerful people. And Rev. Andrew Young guy really involved.

292
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:50,000
And again, he's a brilliant guy. We have some different opinions today about what happened with that strike.

293
00:45:50,000 --> 00:45:54,000
But he did a lot of stuff.

294
00:45:54,000 --> 00:46:02,000
So many of us, the folks that went to jail, he did good stuff to help people to want to go to jail.

295
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:04,000
I had a lot of young blacks.

296
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:09,000
And what I did that was so important for me that we don't visit much.

297
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:12,000
But I found so many people that were in trouble before.

298
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:15,000
That's Rev. Andrew Young black male I'm talking about right now.

299
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:18,000
So we had them as guards for the hospital workers.

300
00:46:18,000 --> 00:46:22,000
And I used to have a bunch of young black male who come to me in the morning.

301
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:25,000
And I used to have a baby woman go to jail to this.

302
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:28,000
And so we would have them blinded to go to jail.

303
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:31,000
Because when they went to jail, they took over the jail.

304
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:35,000
See, they were peeping up in the jail over and over again.

305
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:38,000
So they go in as trustees, they go in whatever.

306
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:43,000
So when I was not able to go to jail, we made sure we had folk already there to protect him.

307
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:46,000
And all of the other people we had folk in jail.

308
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:50,000
And the thing that had been so good for me after that hospital strike,

309
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:53,000
all of these guys went back to school.

310
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:55,000
They're the one of them that's a minister today.

311
00:46:55,000 --> 00:46:59,000
But they changed it like they needed something to hope on.

312
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:03,000
They need to be responsible or somebody to see them or somebody.

313
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:07,000
So they used to be lined up and just to go to jail.

314
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:09,000
It was a different time.

315
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:11,000
It was really a different time.

316
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:14,000
I think the hospital strike changed South Carolina.

317
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:16,000
It really did.

318
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:19,000
It brought a lot of things to human affairs commission.

319
00:47:19,000 --> 00:47:22,000
But it made people feel like I am somebody.

320
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:26,000
The blacks began to get elected to public office.

321
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:31,000
No blacks were elected to public office before that hospital strike.

322
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:34,000
So it made all the difference in the world.

323
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:36,000
Okay.

324
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:37,000
Go ahead.

325
00:47:37,000 --> 00:47:40,000
Tell me more about your contribution to the strike.

326
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:42,000
What role did you play?

327
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:48,000
Well, again, what I did mostly, I was a person of four came to.

328
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:50,000
With problems and stuff like that.

329
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:51,000
And what was going to go on?

330
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:54,000
And how do you solve those kind of problems?

331
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:57,000
And I would be working in the mattress factories five and a half days a week.

332
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:00,000
But I would know exactly what was going on.

333
00:48:00,000 --> 00:48:05,000
You know, one other thing I did doing, I used to smoke up to that strike.

334
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:10,000
When I go to jail, I would never have any habit that I had to have.

335
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:14,000
So I haven't smoked since 1969.

336
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:18,000
But people depended on me for a lot of things.

337
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:23,000
And during the curfew, I would be one of the few people that would be out doing the curfew.

338
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:30,000
There was a vice president of the medical university that I really would like to get some recognition for at some point.

339
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:32,000
His name was William Huffitz, white guy.

340
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:37,000
And again, the final name was Poit his son on a seafood restaurant, now in Folly Road.

341
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:43,000
But him and I used to meet during the curfew.

342
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:50,000
And he would tell me where the hospital trustees were, what they were going on inside.

343
00:48:50,000 --> 00:48:54,000
And I can tell him where I'm Rev. Andrew Young and everybody else of the union.

344
00:48:54,000 --> 00:48:58,000
And how can we bring these two groups together?

345
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:06,000
And we would make proposals to each other where he would go back and say to the trustees and what I would go and say to the folks that were working with.

346
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:12,000
And we were able to do that until we got the trustees and the hospital worker leadership to meet in most corners.

347
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:15,000
Up there, away from everybody.

348
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:20,000
And they asked me to come along to ask them a question.

349
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:24,000
And the hospital worker had about 10 demands.

350
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:31,000
And what we did was, anytime they got the one that the trustees could deal with, I would let them fight over.

351
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:33,000
We just skipped that one.

352
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:35,000
And we were able to solve eight of them.

353
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:41,000
That day, and the trustees were saying to them at that point, we thought you were awful people.

354
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:44,000
And they thought the trustees were awful people.

355
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:47,000
But other folks were promoting who these two groups were not.

356
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:51,000
And if you can meet with people, you can reach them.

357
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:52,000
You don't even have to agree.

358
00:49:52,000 --> 00:49:54,000
But you can reach them.

359
00:49:54,000 --> 00:50:01,000
And that's how that hospital strike began to come to an end because of that meeting that we were able to put together.

360
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:11,000
So in part, you're, you play the key role in the back channel negotiations.

361
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:15,000
But you're also a trusted advisor to the workers.

362
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:24,000
And then you'd also mentioned about kind of working the street crew and coordinating those efforts.

363
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:26,000
Yeah, I see myself as a person.

364
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:30,000
I watch the them and put all of this equipment together.

365
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:37,000
But I always saw myself as a guy that set the prop, build the stage, set it, not the player, not the star.

366
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:40,000
But to be able to make sure that people can start.

367
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:42,000
And that's what I did.

368
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:45,000
I'll be able to set stages for folks to play on.

369
00:50:45,000 --> 00:50:48,000
And that the good people come in and play on it.

370
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:54,000
Now, as a, as the strike became more closely identified with SCLC,

371
00:50:54,000 --> 00:51:01,000
I'd imagine that officially it, you know, they were advocating nonviolent strategies.

372
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:07,000
Did you find yourself in tension with some of the SCLC leaders at that point?

373
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:08,000
Not at all.

374
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:10,000
I don't have a problem at any.

375
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:11,000
I didn't have a problem with that.

376
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:12,000
I still don't.

377
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:15,000
I had a problem with SCLC in the union on another note.

378
00:51:15,000 --> 00:51:22,000
And I wanted them to send the hospital worker leaders into some training.

379
00:51:22,000 --> 00:51:26,000
So they would be prepared to take over when the strike was over.

380
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:28,000
And they was refusing to do that.

381
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:34,000
They were using this mootry all over the country as a spokesman to get more unions or going all kinds of stuff.

382
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:38,000
But they were never, they were not training them to be able to run an office.

383
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:45,000
And there was no way that you can go from hospital workers to an administrative running union dues and all the other stuff that came in.

384
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:48,000
So I had a real problem with them in that area.

385
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:50,000
But not in nonviolent.

386
00:51:50,000 --> 00:51:52,000
I don't have a problem with nonviolent.

387
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:54,000
I just can't do it myself.

388
00:51:54,000 --> 00:51:57,000
But I didn't have a problem with that.

389
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:03,000
And for the most part, things remained peaceful in the streets of Charleston.

390
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:10,000
And then you had a heavy military presence and law enforcement and mass arrests.

391
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:15,000
Well, you know, one thing I told the FBI that they came to me quite a few times.

392
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:22,000
But they, they, that in Charleston, because they were concerned about riots and guns and stuff.

393
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:25,000
And I said, you know, we would never have a riot in Charleston.

394
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:27,000
We'll have a war.

395
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:29,000
Because we equipped a fight.

396
00:52:29,000 --> 00:52:32,000
We got all equipment and everything.

397
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:34,000
And we got access down to the street and everything.

398
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:36,000
So it's not about that.

399
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:40,000
And we, you're not going to find us burning down our community or any of those things.

400
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:42,000
We just want to be treated fairly.

401
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:46,000
But weapons, handguns and stuff is not any weapon.

402
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:49,000
They are all the stuff that you use and walk.

403
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:52,000
And they understood that very much.

404
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:55,000
The head of, let's lay it out, stayed law enforcement.

405
00:52:55,000 --> 00:53:00,000
He began to, matter of fact, one of the persons that we was one of the,

406
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:07,000
the people that was passing the information on was a guy that was working for the federal government.

407
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:12,000
I never learned until later on doing that time that, that,

408
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:19,000
that our, our as agent is really somebody that carry guns that can arrest people and all of that stuff.

409
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:21,000
I didn't know that until after that.

410
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:24,000
But they, you know, they, I was one of those guys.

411
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:28,000
And we were able to, to deal with that.

412
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:32,000
He left tongue and one day the, not too far from where we are.

413
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:38,000
The head of SLED Chief J.P. "Pete" Strom brought him back to Charleston.

414
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:45,000
And he was in the back of the car chief called me and said that he wanted me to meet with him with my mind.

415
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:48,000
And I told us that you got the damn power.

416
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:51,000
Anywhere you want me to be, you know, you can make me be sober.

417
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:53,000
But, what are you asking me that?

418
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:56,000
So he told me to meet him up on the motel right on, thought just a road.

419
00:53:56,000 --> 00:53:58,000
He had five o'clock that evening.

420
00:53:58,000 --> 00:54:02,000
And I got in my car after mattress factory downtown.

421
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:08,000
And they had police also lined up from downtown Charleston to that motel.

422
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:11,000
I could see the cars that I could go by.

423
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:12,000
And I mean, I was young.

424
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:15,000
I just wanted to tell this thing that anybody ever could do.

425
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:19,000
When I got in the parking lot where the chief for me saw his car.

426
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:25,000
I got out of my car and I ran into trunk of my car and left the trunk and just stood there.

427
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:29,000
And I mean, these guys was all over the parking lot not knowing what the hell to do.

428
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:34,000
You know, and I just looked in the trunk for good while I didn't have that plan.

429
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:39,000
And I said, and there's no reason that that didn't kill me at that particular time.

430
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:41,000
I still flashed back on that.

431
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:43,000
That was really dumb.

432
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:48,000
And I went over to the chief car and he, he didn't tell me again what he was there for.

433
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:51,000
And that, that's guy knew about it.

434
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:55,000
And that there was some plans to kill me.

435
00:54:55,000 --> 00:55:01,000
And what he was there for is that he wanted to really be able to give me some protection.

436
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:04,000
And I told him that chief, please don't protect me.

437
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:14,000
Please don't do nothing to help me, you know, y'all help King and Kennedy and all of these people, y'all, please don't save me.

438
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:18,000
And at that point, we knew who was wanting to do something to me.

439
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:23,000
We already knew that there was some other white union men that had some problems with me in my pleasure.

440
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:26,000
So we were aware of that and protecting our own stuff.

441
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:31,000
But we just, so tell them we can have our own protection at that point.

442
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:36,000
You had some sort of apparatus for protecting yourself and protecting the strike leaders?

443
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:37,000
Yeah.

444
00:55:37,000 --> 00:55:43,000
Yeah. And we, and our apparatus was offensive.

445
00:55:43,000 --> 00:55:47,000
I, today don't believe in defense.

446
00:55:47,000 --> 00:55:50,000
I don't know nothing that ever been won on defense.

447
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:52,000
Are you playing ball or anything else?

448
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:54,000
Everything is won on defense.

449
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:58,000
And what we did was that what would happen if something happened?

450
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:01,000
All kinds of stuff would happen if something happened.

451
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:04,000
And it was all, you know, it was all out there.

452
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:07,000
What, what could happen?

453
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:10,000
So we, we, and we operated that way.

454
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:20,000
We did stuff like, I have a Nazi, the worst part they had with arrest and stuff with I have a Nazi one that night,

455
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:23,000
that evening they were supposed to be ending the strike.

456
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:29,000
And we were waiting at Brooks Motel, which was the black motel that we, our office, end up being.

457
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:39,000
And the governor called me, had one of the blacks that was a part of his group to call me over there and said he wanted to talk to me, Governor Robert E. McNair.

458
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:45,000
And he went over and the governor said Bill Saunders, what I want you to do for me is that I want you to go to Morris Brown AME Church and Emanuel AME Church (likely) tonight.

459
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:49,000
And I want you to tell the people that we want end the strike tomorrow.

460
00:56:49,000 --> 00:56:51,000
Don't worry about it. Just tell them.

461
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:56,000
And they got enough faith in you that they would believe you and everybody would go home happy.

462
00:56:56,000 --> 00:57:00,000
And I said, okay, governor, let me, let me call you back.

463
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:02,000
So I went and I thought about it.

464
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:05,000
And I went back and I had to call the governor.

465
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:08,000
Now, to go to him, why don't you send me a telegram?

466
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:16,000
And I would go to the church and I would read the telegram from you that you're going to end this strike tomorrow.

467
00:57:16,000 --> 00:57:19,000
And he said, Bill Saunders, let me get back to you.

468
00:57:19,000 --> 00:57:21,000
He called me back about 15 minutes.

469
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:24,000
He said that he could not send me a telegram.

470
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:27,000
But he will end this strike tomorrow.

471
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:31,000
All I had to do was go and tell the people because the people got faith in nothing to do it.

472
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:34,000
I said, okay, governor, I'll do it.

473
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:39,000
And I went, Dr. Avonati was on his car leading on a car reading a Bible.

474
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:46,000
And I told him to go, Reverend, Reverend Avonati did nothing I could do.

475
00:57:46,000 --> 00:57:50,000
And I got in my car and I went to Johns Island, South Carolina.

476
00:57:50,000 --> 00:57:54,000
And they arrested maybe 200 people that night from that church.

477
00:57:54,000 --> 00:57:57,000
I mean, stuff just went there.

478
00:57:57,000 --> 00:57:59,000
But I just went home.

479
00:57:59,000 --> 00:58:01,000
Because I knew he was lying to me.

480
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:06,000
But he was setting me up that I was one that people were going to hate.

481
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:09,000
Because I was going to tell them a lie.

482
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:14,000
And that's when that strike got to where they're going to end.

483
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:20,000
And Hugh C. Lane Sr, who you know, a little bit about God involved to talk to somebody in the Nixon Administration.

484
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:25,000
And they called him and asked Hugh Lane Sr, what can we do to end this strike?

485
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:29,000
He said he's a bizz banker and it's cold business man, like my life.

486
00:58:29,000 --> 00:58:31,000
He said, cut off the money.

487
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:36,000
HEW. has given medical college about 75 million dollars, cut off all the money.

488
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:42,000
And tell them they can end the strike and tell people that they're doing it because they want to be good to the community.

489
00:58:42,000 --> 00:58:46,000
Or tell them that they're doing it because you all made them do it.

490
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:49,000
But that's what you need to do is to cut off the money.

491
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:52,000
And then he came back to the Community Relations Service,

492
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:58,000
which you got some papers on and said that, tell Ask Me to hold off another two weeks or so,

493
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:00,000
because he had something working.

494
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:05,000
At that point, we were working with the Longshoremen because they were about to shut down the post.

495
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:10,000
At that point also, I asked them to not do that.

496
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:14,000
And we would just wait and then they ended the strike.

497
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:16,000
But it was that thing.

498
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:22,000
And a lot of people take credit for a humiliating and a lot of folk was involved in that ending.

499
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:28,000
And one thing that is so hard for me with it, and you were talking to me earlier about my own bitterness and my hurt.

500
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:37,000
But you would find nowhere where anybody in Charleston got credit for doing anything good with that trait.

501
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:40,000
It was SCLC and the union. They did everything.

502
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:46,000
No, not the local people did anything for the lives and stuff on the night, wasn't that.

503
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:48,000
I mean, Andrew Young blew up.

504
00:59:48,000 --> 00:59:51,000
I mean, he got to be a Congress and all kinds of stuff.

505
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:53,000
That was a new beginning for him.

506
00:59:53,000 --> 00:59:57,000
And I'm not angry about that because that's what he does best.

507
00:59:57,000 --> 01:00:02,000
But some people from here needed to be credit because we the one that did the stage.

508
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:04,000
We did all the stage set in the prop.

509
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:07,000
And we the one that took all of the beating.

510
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:10,000
How did you feel about the settlement?

511
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:16,000
The settlement to me was really, really nothing.

512
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:22,000
But I think to me, we were going to make our own type of settlement in that.

513
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:26,000
And that's how come one of the things that we wondered was the South Carolina Human Affairs Commission, which came out of that.

514
01:00:26,000 --> 01:00:28,000
But folks are doing the only thing.

515
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:31,000
The registered voting and different stuff happening in the city of Charleston.

516
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:35,000
We end up not too long after having six Blacks on City Council.

517
01:00:35,000 --> 01:00:40,000
When we had no elected Blacks on City Council, people elected the House of Representatives.

518
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:42,000
We had people elected the County Council.

519
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:46,000
And the schoolboys got elected the schoolboys.

520
01:00:46,000 --> 01:00:50,000
So people have to be responsible for themselves.

521
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:53,000
All you can do set the stage for them to do it.

522
01:00:53,000 --> 01:00:55,000
Now, if they don't want, I got 10 kids.

523
01:00:55,000 --> 01:00:58,000
And I said, I don't want y'all to have the excuse that I had.

524
01:00:58,000 --> 01:00:59,000
I didn't have access.

525
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:00,000
I'm going to give you access.

526
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:03,000
And if you don't use the damn access, that's your problem.

527
01:01:03,000 --> 01:01:05,000
But I'm going to make sure you have access.

528
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:06,000
And a lot of folks are calling me.

529
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:09,000
None of my kids like me telling me 25.

530
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:14,000
I mean, I literally hate me when they call me awful father.

531
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:19,000
But, you know, I had one of my kids got in trouble graduating from high school.

532
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:25,000
He goes with two kids and they stole wine out of the grocery store and got caught.

533
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:31,000
And then my wife and other daughters, they're going to be mad at the store.

534
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:33,000
That is because they stole a wine from them.

535
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:37,000
And then they're going to say, other kids leading, Mike, I said no.

536
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:39,000
My kid had to be the leader.

537
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:40,000
He can't be my kid.

538
01:01:40,000 --> 01:01:42,000
And look at other kids leading him.

539
01:01:42,000 --> 01:01:43,000
He was great.

540
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:44,000
No, he's the leader.

541
01:01:44,000 --> 01:01:46,000
They all hate me.

542
01:01:46,000 --> 01:01:49,000
I said they really, really hate me.

543
01:01:49,000 --> 01:01:51,000
My God's grace up till here.

544
01:01:51,000 --> 01:01:54,000
But you have to be responsible.

545
01:01:54,000 --> 01:01:56,000
You have a bad childhood I had.

546
01:01:56,000 --> 01:02:00,000
I used to do with some of Rev. Andrew Young people with the bad childhood of being mistreated.

547
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:03,000
It doesn't give you an excuse to hurt people.

548
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:05,000
It doesn't give you an excuse to kill people.

549
01:02:05,000 --> 01:02:10,000
A lot of folks are doing right now just because somebody did something to them.

550
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:13,000
You know, they got a right to go and hurt other people.

551
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:15,000
That doesn't give you the right to do anything.

552
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:18,000
You've still got a chance to do something.

553
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:24,000
From the hospital worker strike, you went right into the sanitation worker strike.

554
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:27,000
A lot of times gets mist.

555
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:30,000
Yeah, we had both of those things going right after that.

556
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:32,000
we had the sanitation [strike].

557
01:02:32,000 --> 01:02:37,000
Some of the stuff, even some of the local hospitals sort of went on.

558
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:39,000
There were no settlements there.

559
01:02:39,000 --> 01:02:43,000
And one of the reasons I'm glad you brought that back up, because one of the reasons that we had,

560
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:47,000
we went against the medical college because there was a state institution.

561
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:49,000
There were a lot of small hospitals.

562
01:02:49,000 --> 01:02:54,000
But if we went against the state hospital, then we went against the whole state.

563
01:02:54,000 --> 01:02:57,000
So, anyplace that people were working for the state.

564
01:02:57,000 --> 01:03:00,000
I had to sit-down strikes.

565
01:03:00,000 --> 01:03:02,000
They all began to make minimum wage.

566
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:05,000
All began to have access to training program.

567
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:09,000
All of the stuff that we were fighting for benefited the whole state.

568
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:14,000
And with the sanitation department, we were able to take that over to them.

569
01:03:14,000 --> 01:03:17,000
Because again, they were not being paid minimum wage.

570
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:20,000
Blacks couldn't even drive the truck sanitation.

571
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:26,000
They couldn't even ride in the front of the truck when it's raining until after that sanitation strike.

572
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:30,000
So, we were able to win that.

573
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:35,000
But again, some of my own bitterness is that I trust people.

574
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:38,000
And I trust laws that folk write.

575
01:03:38,000 --> 01:03:42,000
And a lot of times, the laws are just written for a certain period of time.

576
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:46,000
And what they did, what we did, like with the sanitation worker,

577
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:49,000
they had some mean white guys that was running it.

578
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:54,000
So, what we did, and what they did is they switched them and put some mean black guys.

579
01:03:54,000 --> 01:03:58,000
And so, the black guys now, I'm actually, you've been a part of that, okay?

580
01:03:58,000 --> 01:04:02,000
They're mistreating the people worse than these whites ever did.

581
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:07,000
So, it's that kind of stuff that we have to come to griffin.

582
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:11,000
And again, we deal with class, the same class system.

583
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:14,000
And nobody's teaching that.

584
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:19,000
The way that these black men have treated, and not only the black men, the treating black,

585
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:23,000
but we got all these women now working in sanitation department driving trucks

586
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:27,000
and doing all kinds of stuff, and being treated awful.

587
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:30,000
And then, the racism and racism are playing in it.

588
01:04:30,000 --> 01:04:34,000
And all the mistreating men that's coming from black men.

589
01:04:34,000 --> 01:04:43,000
Over the last few years, I know that you've been involved in, in organizing the sanitation workers,

590
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:46,000
other city workers.

591
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:54,000
How did that all come about, is the, I guess, the re-emergence of local 1199 in Charleston?

592
01:04:54,000 --> 01:05:00,000
Well, I guess, you know, folks still come back to me with some of, I guess,

593
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:03,000
being involved and stuff like that.

594
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:08,000
It is hard right now to make people responsible for themselves.

595
01:05:08,000 --> 01:05:09,000
It's very hard.

596
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:15,000
And with the sanitation workers, you refine, they have so much infighting with themselves,

597
01:05:15,000 --> 01:05:18,000
being mistreated, but they see themselves more as the enemy,

598
01:05:18,000 --> 01:05:21,000
so they can fight among themselves and win.

599
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:23,000
And poor people are that way.

600
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:29,000
And I, right now, I sort of backed out of it for the period of time with my own mind.

601
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:36,000
Because I stopped going back over my own life, and you talk about the involvement with, like, in 1980,

602
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:40,000
I wanted to be a senator, one of my biggest ambition to be a state senator.

603
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:45,000
I club 46 people, and they were really elite groups.

604
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:48,000
And I even got some writing votes in 1968.

605
01:05:48,000 --> 01:05:52,000
But in 1980, I ran for the state senator.

606
01:05:52,000 --> 01:05:57,000
And I wanted the Democratic primary, and I wanted the Democratic runoff,

607
01:05:57,000 --> 01:06:00,000
and we were able to do some stuff.

608
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:04,000
But again, doing that election, the NAACP opposed me.

609
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:09,000
And they brought people from Atlanta, Georgia and everywhere, out on the islands,

610
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:12,000
and tell folks that they didn't want me to be elected.

611
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:17,000
And the reason that they didn't want me to be elected is because of my own family background.

612
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:25,000
They wanted a black person to be elected, the first black senator, to have a very good background from their alliance.

613
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:30,000
And they had already made their arrangement, who that person was going to be.

614
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:32,000
And so they wanted me to lose.

615
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:35,000
It was still a very, very close race.

616
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:40,000
And I think the only reason, again, I still lost that race, was because of Ronald Reagan.

617
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:45,000
And it was the first year that white people began to pull the mass to leave it.

618
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:47,000
After that point, they didn't do that.

619
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:51,000
But they wanted I. DeQuincey Newman to be the first black senator.

620
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:54,000
They already made a arrangement that Alexander, who you know,

621
01:06:54,000 --> 01:07:00,000
these people, President Carter, Trump, was going to resign from the Senate to get a judgeship.

622
01:07:00,000 --> 01:07:06,000
And they're going to have a special election for I.D. to be that, be that trust black senator.

623
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:11,000
So a lot of my bitterness runs very, very deep.

624
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:15,000
I'm not a one-sided thing.

625
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:21,000
My hopes with a lot of stuff, I just got sidetracked by people.

626
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:30,000
The end of the ACP opposed you in the primary and the runoff, but in the general as well?

627
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:31,000
Yeah, the general.

628
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:34,000
And they backed from a panel?

629
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:37,000
Well, they didn't back anybody. They didn't come back and McComb.

630
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:41,000
But you would find that it was back in McComb.

631
01:07:41,000 --> 01:07:47,000
The Robert Ford, and then that particular point.

632
01:07:47,000 --> 01:07:51,000
And they brought some confusion like they're doing with the role of the thing.

633
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:55,000
Robert put up some tickets, and they would put my name on it with a Republican.

634
01:07:55,000 --> 01:07:58,000
And Trump, for example, would not, you know, just get that something.

635
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:00,000
I had so loud or something.

636
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:04,000
It's easy to mess with people that are not totally engaged.

637
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:10,000
And that's I keep hoping that we can come up with a way that we're going to be able to give people the truth.

638
01:08:10,000 --> 01:08:17,000
The grandmaccano doing that run with me, he would tell people that he was going to build a coup or a bridge.

639
01:08:17,000 --> 01:08:23,000
And I would say, for no freshmen senator in the status of Gailan, it could build any damn bridge.

640
01:08:23,000 --> 01:08:26,000
You know, but they believed it.

641
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:35,000
And they took 25 years later before Jim Clyburn and Rob Nell and some of them could put that bridge together, send the homies in them.

642
01:08:35,000 --> 01:08:39,000
But we love, as Americans we love people that lie to us.

643
01:08:39,000 --> 01:08:42,000
We love policies in the toughest lives.

644
01:08:42,000 --> 01:08:45,000
And then we can fight them, say they lie later on.

645
01:08:45,000 --> 01:08:52,000
But I have a lot of bitterness in terms of with my own life in terms of what I could have done.

646
01:08:52,000 --> 01:08:57,000
If I had the right kind of family background and those kinds of stuff.

647
01:08:57,000 --> 01:09:00,000
And you need to start off with something.

648
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:05,000
You know, being the first generation of my family to go through or to attempt to do anything.

649
01:09:05,000 --> 01:09:08,000
It's not a good place to be.

650
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:13,000
Somebody asked me recently, you know, am I training anybody to take my place?

651
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:16,000
I would wish this life on the damn.

652
01:09:16,000 --> 01:09:21,000
So I want nobody to live this life that I have lived.

653
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:24,000
I want to, I tell God I want to see it through.

654
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:26,000
But I, you know, I don't want to change anything.

655
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:29,000
But I don't know, I don't want to wish it on anybody.

656
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:32,000
It's been very, very hard.

657
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:35,000
And being misunderstood most of the time.

658
01:09:35,000 --> 01:09:36,000
Talk people.

659
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:42,000
And most people don't know that this country was structured so well for radio.

660
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:49,000
It said that nobody could own a radio station unless serving the community, yet to serve the community before you make a nickel.

661
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:52,000
You can even gotten into TV.

662
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:57,000
So you had to, when I was doing radio, I couldn't run about five commercials.

663
01:09:57,000 --> 01:10:00,000
At one time, then I had to do something for the public.

664
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:03,000
Nine days can run three hours with a commercial.

665
01:10:03,000 --> 01:10:05,000
And then nobody cares.

666
01:10:05,000 --> 01:10:07,000
Running Reagan again made those changes.

667
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:15,000
But we were able to really start people into radio where they really believe in what we were doing.

668
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:21,000
We had people that would take off the knob that you changed the station, the family.

669
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:23,000
You could not switch.

670
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:27,000
That nobody in the house could change the station.

671
01:10:27,000 --> 01:10:30,000
Our station got the number one rating.

672
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:32,000
We had a daytime radio station.

673
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:35,000
We got the number one rating out of about 27 stations.

674
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:38,000
And Folk came at me all over the lawsuit.

675
01:10:38,000 --> 01:10:41,000
Said that there was something that we were doing illegal.

676
01:10:41,000 --> 01:10:44,000
And I was like, what are the reasons that they sent out?

677
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:47,000
And I've been having them bring it to church or something like that.

678
01:10:47,000 --> 01:10:57,000
But what was happening at that time, with parents, black parents, I mean the kids and everybody listen to what their parents listen to in the radio.

679
01:10:57,000 --> 01:11:02,000
And on Sundays, we were number one because we did gospel and talk and jazz.

680
01:11:02,000 --> 01:11:04,000
So it was really something.

681
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:06,000
And I just, I loved it.

682
01:11:06,000 --> 01:11:10,000
I love anything that you don't have a script.

683
01:11:10,000 --> 01:11:13,000
We're getting away now from teaching.

684
01:11:13,000 --> 01:11:16,000
And I'm worried about your professors and stuff.

685
01:11:16,000 --> 01:11:21,000
That teaching kids to think, how do you do this without a computer?

686
01:11:21,000 --> 01:11:23,000
How do you do this?

687
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:25,000
You don't have any electricity.

688
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:27,000
Those kinds of stuff.

689
01:11:27,000 --> 01:11:29,000
Even the cook.

690
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:33,000
What happened if you don't have any gas or electricity?

691
01:11:33,000 --> 01:11:35,000
Can you still eat?

692
01:11:35,000 --> 01:11:39,000
Those kinds of things is frightening for me.

693
01:11:39,000 --> 01:11:44,000
Because we are making robots out of young people.

694
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:47,000
I got some grandkids that I want to teach some stuff.

695
01:11:47,000 --> 01:11:51,000
But they got all kinds of little gadgets that they're playing with.

696
01:11:51,000 --> 01:11:59,000
I've watched kids riding cars with parents and never look up to see whether car coming to hit the car or any those kinds of stuff.

697
01:11:59,000 --> 01:12:07,000
We really are learning our country to go in a way that scares the hell out of me.

698
01:12:07,000 --> 01:12:11,000
But I don't mind having problems with enemies or anything like that.

699
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:13,000
Now we can do something.

700
01:12:13,000 --> 01:12:16,000
We're dealing with the road across the island right now.

701
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:19,000
We have brought everybody that from Johns Island, South Carolina together.

702
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:22,000
You know, ex-Clansemen and farmers and all of those.

703
01:12:22,000 --> 01:12:24,000
We all together.

704
01:12:24,000 --> 01:12:28,000
And what we do, I've started it myself with this concerned citizen.

705
01:12:28,000 --> 01:12:31,000
We don't talk about religion and we don't talk about politics.

706
01:12:31,000 --> 01:12:33,000
We just talk about the issue.

707
01:12:33,000 --> 01:12:36,000
You know, if you're dealing with the issue, that's where you are.

708
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:41,000
And you don't have to worry about any of these things if you're dealing with right and wrong.

709
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:43,000
But we put all the stuff in it.

710
01:12:43,000 --> 01:12:44,000
Is it right?

711
01:12:44,000 --> 01:12:46,000
You know, or is it wrong?

712
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:48,000
So it doesn't matter who the hell you are.

713
01:12:48,000 --> 01:12:51,000
It's a right and that's what I do.

714
01:12:51,000 --> 01:12:53,000
What are you proudest?

715
01:12:53,000 --> 01:13:01,000
My proudest is that I'm 76 years old and never been indicted by my government.

716
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:07,000
That was one of my biggest fears still looming over me.

717
01:13:07,000 --> 01:13:11,000
But my government is the one that get rid of most people like me.

718
01:13:11,000 --> 01:13:16,000
And so I've just lived this long and not been indicted.

719
01:13:16,000 --> 01:13:21,000
I've even came very close a couple of times, even getting me off the public service commission.

720
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:23,000
It was one of those kinds.

721
01:13:23,000 --> 01:13:25,000
I threatened indicted men and stuff.

722
01:13:25,000 --> 01:13:28,000
But I am kind of proud of that.

723
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:34,000
Who taught you to organize?

724
01:13:34,000 --> 01:13:37,000
Nobody.

725
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:39,000
No, no.

726
01:13:39,000 --> 01:13:44,000
You know, that's one of the things I've gotten in the trouble with interviews like you before.

727
01:13:44,000 --> 01:13:48,000
Because somebody has to teach you.

728
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:54,000
And the biggest teacher I've had in anything is losing.

729
01:13:55,000 --> 01:14:01,000
If you continue to lose, you find ways to make it work.

730
01:14:01,000 --> 01:14:03,000
And that's the thing.

731
01:14:03,000 --> 01:14:09,000
I had to learn even in my elementary school to be able to work from a negative or a positive.

732
01:14:09,000 --> 01:14:14,000
Because I never had a teacher that liked me from where I stood.

733
01:14:14,000 --> 01:14:17,000
And then I would ask questions whether kids would not do.

734
01:14:17,000 --> 01:14:20,000
So nobody taught me.

735
01:14:20,000 --> 01:14:25,000
But if you know the needs, if you know the needs, you can work up a formula.

736
01:14:25,000 --> 01:14:31,000
One of my teacher, my algebra teacher, really hated me with a passion.

737
01:14:31,000 --> 01:14:36,000
And he gave a test one day when I came out for one day, he gave a test.

738
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:39,000
And I was able to do all of the problems.

739
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:44,000
But he still mocked my paper wrong because I didn't use the formula that the book had.

740
01:14:44,000 --> 01:14:47,000
And I created my own formula in my head.

741
01:14:48,000 --> 01:14:50,000
And he said it had to be that.

742
01:14:50,000 --> 01:14:53,000
And I raised a lot of hell in the classroom.

743
01:14:53,000 --> 01:14:56,000
And they read and got the principles.

744
01:14:56,000 --> 01:15:01,000
When the principal came, and I'd say, please, just give him the problem because he's also a math.

745
01:15:01,000 --> 01:15:05,000
And he did it all together differently.

746
01:15:05,000 --> 01:15:08,000
And so I was vindicated at that.

747
01:15:08,000 --> 01:15:11,000
And he said that it doesn't matter how you do it.

748
01:15:11,000 --> 01:15:14,000
Can you check there and do you have a way to do it?

749
01:15:14,000 --> 01:15:19,000
And that's the thing that's important, to be able to devise your own formula.

750
01:15:19,000 --> 01:15:24,000
And one other thing I'm carrying out, I really teach, I still teach some in schools,

751
01:15:24,000 --> 01:15:29,000
but that you've got to learn to enjoy the process.

752
01:15:29,000 --> 01:15:32,000
Most people do not enjoy the process.

753
01:15:32,000 --> 01:15:34,000
They're looking for the end results.

754
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:39,000
And that's why I ask you all the time, I start to ask him earlier, what do you want to be when you grow up?

755
01:15:39,000 --> 01:15:43,000
Because if you get the point you already grown up, you don't lost it.

756
01:15:43,000 --> 01:15:48,000
You've got to have some ambition to want to do something beyond what you're doing.

757
01:15:48,000 --> 01:15:54,000
The process, I never have about three, four, five years of playing at the most.

758
01:15:54,000 --> 01:15:58,000
But it evolves for me.

759
01:15:58,000 --> 01:16:04,000
But if you satisfy what you're doing, I used to get so angry at the black teachers.

760
01:16:04,000 --> 01:16:07,000
